full_text: @witfnews @BucknellU E-cigarettes don't produce carbon monoxide unless cranked up on a dry hit that no vapor would ever inhale.  Carbon monoxide (CO) is a product of combustion.  E-cigarettes are not combustion-based.  Numerous studies show blood CO plummets when smokers switch to nicotine vaping.
